<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Git on KevCaz's Website</title><link>https://kevcaz.github.io/tags/git/</link><description>Recent content in Git on KevCaz's Website</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en-us</language><copyright>Content under CC0 1.0 Universal unless otherwise specified.</copyright><lastBuildDate>Tue, 11 Jan 2022 00:00:00 +0000</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://kevcaz.github.io/tags/git/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Basic Git server on my Raspberry Pi</title><link>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2022/01/2022-01-11_basic_git_server/</link><pubDate>Tue, 11 Jan 2022 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2022/01/2022-01-11_basic_git_server/</guid><description>&lt;p>As mentioned in my &lt;a href="../../notes/rapsberrypi/nextcloud_server/">previous post&lt;/a>, I have recently started using my Raspberry Pi as a server and I decided to try to host a basic Git server.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>As explained in the chapter &lt;a href="https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Git-on-the-Server-The-Protocols">&amp;ldquo;Git on the Server&amp;rdquo;&lt;/a> of Pro Git&lt;sup id="fnref:1">&lt;a href="#fn:1" class="footnote-ref" role="doc-noteref">1&lt;/a>&lt;/sup>, among other protocols, Git supports SSH and it is quite straightforward to setup a basic Git server via this protocol. As I can access my Raspberry Pi via ssh, I decided to give it a try! I first connected to it as user &lt;code>pi&lt;/code> (&lt;code>ssh pi@raspberry.local&lt;/code>), a user that is listed as a super user, and I created a new user: &lt;code>git&lt;/code> (this is one way suggested in Pro Git).&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Prezto's aliases for git</title><link>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2019/11/2019-11-01_prezto_s_aliases/</link><pubDate>Fri, 01 Nov 2019 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2019/11/2019-11-01_prezto_s_aliases/</guid><description>&lt;p>A few days ago, as I was having a look at the list of aliases I use with
&lt;a href="http://zsh.sourceforge.net/">Zsh&lt;/a>, I realized that there was a ton of aliases
