&lt;/div>&lt;p>I had two thoughts while I was examining those:&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Emoticons in commit messages for manuscripts</title><link>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2019/05/2019-05-20_emoticons_in_commit/</link><pubDate>Mon, 20 May 2019 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2019/05/2019-05-20_emoticons_in_commit/</guid><description>&lt;p>I recently wrote a &lt;a href="../../notes/git/commitmessages/">note about using emoticons in a standard way in commit
messages&lt;/a> and I now use them in a standard way following &lt;a href="https://gitmoji.carloscuesta.me/">Gitmoji&lt;/a>. I do so for my code, but I also use &lt;a href="https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2">git&lt;/a> for manuscrits and I also try to standardize the way I use emoticons in that case. Below is the set of emoticons I am currently using for manuscrits:&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>&amp;#x1f4dd; &lt;code>pencil&lt;/code> add a significant piece of writing, paragraph;&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&amp;#x270f;&amp;#xfe0f; &lt;code>pencil2&lt;/code>typos;&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&amp;#x1f4ca; &lt;code>bar_chart&lt;/code> figures added or edited (figure or its caption);&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&amp;#x1f5d1;&amp;#xfe0f; &lt;code>wastebasket&lt;/code> delete an file;&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&amp;#x2728; &lt;code>sparkles&lt;/code> integrate co-author&amp;rsquo;s comment(s)/work;&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&amp;#x1f389; &lt;code>tada&lt;/code> address reviewer&amp;rsquo;s comment(s);&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&amp;#x2b06;&amp;#xfe0f; &lt;code>arrow_up&lt;/code> version submitted;&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&amp;#x1f680; &lt;code>rocket&lt;/code> version accepted.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul></description></item><item><title>Emoticons in commit messages</title><link>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2019/02/2019-02-17_emoticons_in_commit/</link><pubDate>Sun, 17 Feb 2019 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2019/02/2019-02-17_emoticons_in_commit/</guid><description>&lt;p>When you are working on a project with GitHub (or a similar web service based on &lt;i class="fa fa-git" aria-hidden="true">&lt;/i>) that has tens of commits, using emoticons in commit messages makes the search in the history of your project very efficient. To add one emoticon to your commit message, you must use its name (check this &lt;a href="https://www.webfx.com/tools/emoji-cheat-sheet/">cheat sheet&lt;/a>) within colons in the commit message, e.g. &amp;ldquo;add this :emoticon_name:&amp;rdquo;. Personally, I mostly use the following emoticon:&lt;/p></description></item></channel></rss>